The data was fit to a series of unmarked SCR models. Because the data was collected across such a long time frame, I wasn’t sure the best way to estimate the population. So I split the data in 7 2-week increments and estimated the population at each of those ‘primary’ occasions.

Total Abundance

We can look at abundance across all areas at each time period. We can see the CIs are quite broad, which is unsurprising since this is unmarked data. One average, the data suggest there were somewhere between 50-100 sparrows present.

knitr::kable(summary_N2, row.names = F)

Detection

As our effort in each pixel increases, so does our detection. The graph shows the difference in detection for 2 m per 250m^2 pixel vs 200m of transect in a 250m^2 pixel.

Side note: I thought we could maybe get pseudo home-range estimates out, but I don’t think we can because of the way we have to model set up. Oh well.

Habitat Raster Used in Model

Values represent how much of the pixel is estimated to be water vs. vegetation. Higher values indicate less water and more ‘useable habitat.’
